population: Background information

The population data you loaded have three variables: country, year, population.

country contains the country name,

year corresponds to the year data was captured (from 1995 to 2013) with a âYâ prefix. For example, 1995 is âY1995â within the data.

population is the estimated population according to the World Health Organization

Task 1:

Note: The wide format you generate below should look partially like the table below:

country Y1995 Y1996 â¦
Afghanistan 17586073 18415307 â¦

Use pivot_wider() below to transform the population data into wide format via the R code chunk provided below. Also save the data into your R environment (name it however you want) then print a sample of that data using head() or glimpse() within the same R code chunk.

# Place your code below:
population_wide <- population |>
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = year,
    values_from = population
  )

Task 2:

Within the R chunk below, do the following: using the data you saved from Task 1, keep three variables only: country, Y1995, Y2013. Afterwards, create a variable called population_change by using the formula below: Y2013 - Y1995. Afterwards, keep the data rows if and only if the population_change is negative. Save the resulting data into your R envât as countries_shrunk

# Place your code below:
countries_shrunk <- population_wide |>
  select(country, Y1995, Y2013) |>
  mutate(population_change = Y2013 - Y1995) |>
  filter(population_change < 0)

Heart Rate Data and Background

Run the following script to load patient_heart_rate into the R environment:

patient_heart_rate <- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jmtfeliciano/teachingdata/refs/heads/main/patient_heart_rate.csv")

The patient_heart_rate data contains three variables: patient_id, drug1, and drug2

patient_id are patient IDs within their electronic health records

drug1 is the patient heart rate during doctor visit after taking drug 1 for 6 months

drug2 is the patient heart rate during doctor visit after taking drug 2 for 6 months

The data was collected to assess the effectiveness of two drugs to control/lower heart rates.

Task 4:

Note: The long format you generate below should look partially like this table below:

patient_id drug_taken heart_rate
AJ9101 drug1 91
AJ9101 drug2 80
JU9301 drug1 110
â¦ â¦ â¦

Use pivot_longer() below to transform the patient_heart_rate data into long format via the R code chunk provided below. Also save the data into your R environment (name it however you want) then print a sample of that data using head() or glimpse() within the same R code chunk.

# Place your code below:
heart_rate_long <- patient_heart_rate |>
  pivot_longer(
    cols = drug1:drug2, # data to transponse from column names into rows to make it long
    names_to = "drug_taken", # either I will give this you directly or look into partial output
    values_to = "heart_rate" # either I will give this you directly or look into partial output
  )
head(heart_rate_long)

Task 5:

Using data you generated in task 4, generate a box plot where x is drug taken and y is heart rate.

# Place your code below:
ggplot(data = heart_rate_long,
       aes(x = drug_taken, y = heart_rate)) +
  geom_boxplot()

Task 6:

The patient_heart_rate data was collected to assess the effectiveness of two drugs to control/lower heart rates. Based on the visualization you created in Task 5, do you believe that a preliminary suggestive evidence exists to suggest that one drug is better in controlling heart rates? If so, which drug is better? (Hint and you may not see this hint in the exam: Focus on comparing the approximate value of the median. Also consider where Q1 and Q3 resides between the two drugs, which spans the middle 50% of the data.)

Your response (along these lines): The median heart rate for Drug 1 is approximately 96 with Q1 and Q3, the central 50% of the heart rate data, lying approximately between 94 and 101. Meanwhile, the median heart rate for Drug 2 is approximately 73 with Q1 and Q3, the central 50% of the heart rate data, lying approximately between 69 and 79. Given the significant gap between these heart rate numbers, there is preliminary suggestive evidence to indicate that Drug 2 might be a better drug in lowering heart rate.

Task 7:

Using the data you generated in Task 4, compute the exact median heart rate after drug 1 and drug 2 intakes using one or more dplyr verbs:

# Place your code below:
heart_rate_long |>
  group_by(drug_taken) |>
  summarize(median_heart_rate = median(heart_rate, na.rm = T)) # I named it median_heart_rate but you can name it however you want
# A tibble: 2 Ã 2
  drug_taken median_heart_rate
  <chr>                  <dbl>
1 drug1                   96.5
2 drug2                   72

Extra Material

To those with statistics background, ggstatsplot is an excellent tool for plotting box plots and it does the relevant statistical test for you.

You are not allowed you use this for your homework and exam in this course. But you are free to use it for your final project.

# if you haven't installed, run: install.packages("ggstatsplot")
library(ggstatsplot)
You can cite this package as:
     Patil, I. (2021). Visualizations with statistical details: The 'ggstatsplot' approach.
     Journal of Open Source Software, 6(61), 3167, doi:10.21105/joss.03167
ggbetweenstats(data = heart_rate_long, x = drug_taken, y = heart_rate)
ggbetweenstats(data = heart_rate_long, x = drug_taken, y = heart_rate, type = "nonparametric")
